# Red Hat Connectivity Link Tutorial

This project is a tutorial demonstrating Red Hat Connectivity Link 1.3 on OpenShift.

## Product Context

- Red Hat Connectivity Link 1.3 (based on upstream Kuadrant)
- Uses Kubernetes Gateway API as its foundation
- Policies attach to Gateway and HTTPRoute resources
- Runs on OpenShift Container Platform 4.19+
- Uses OpenShift Cluster Ingress Operator as default gateway controller

## Tutorial Scope

- Single-cluster deployment (no multi-cluster, no DNSPolicy)
- RateLimitPolicy, AuthPolicy, TLSPolicy demonstrations
- AuthPolicy uses OIDC with Red Hat build of Keycloak 26.4
- Observability with Prometheus + Perses dashboards (via Cluster Observability Operator) + optional Tempo tracing
- Simple REST backend services (developed later)

## Key Conventions

- Prefer Operators (installed via OLM) over Helm charts
- Use plain Kubernetes/OpenShift manifest YAML files
- Keep manifests simple and readable for tutorial purposes
- Namespace: `kuadrant-system` for operator, `api-gateway` for gateway, `keycloak` for Keycloak, app namespaces as needed
- Use `oc` CLI commands (OpenShift), not plain `kubectl`
- Reference official Red Hat docs: https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_connectivity_link/1.3/

## API Versions

- Kuadrant CRDs: `kuadrant.io/v1` (RateLimitPolicy, AuthPolicy)
- TLSPolicy: `kuadrant.io/v1alpha2`
- Gateway API: `gateway.networking.k8s.io/v1`
- Kuadrant operand: `kuadrant.io/v1beta1`
- Perses CRDs: `perses.dev/v1alpha2` (PersesDashboard, PersesDatasource, PersesGlobalDatasource)
- Cluster Observability Operator UIPlugin: `observability.openshift.io/v1alpha1`
